```

The `java.util.Vector` class realizes thread-safety by qualifying every public method that performs read or write access on its internal `Object[] elementData` array with the `synchronized` modifier. Each such method therefore acquires the monitor associated with the `Vector` instance itself before executing array manipulation or structural update logic, including incrementing the `modCount` field. Because the intrinsic lock serializes all invocations of these methods, any two threads cannot interleave array reads and writes on the same `Vector` instance. Consequently, the fail-fast iterator mechanism never observes a structural modification performed without holding the same lock, eliminating the conditions under which a `ConcurrentModificationException` is thrown. When the `ThreadSafeQueue` implementation further guards composite operations (`dequeue`) with its own `synchronized` methods while delegating storage to the already-synchronized `Vector`, both single-element access and the check-then-act sequence remain atomic with respect to other threads.

